{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4815d6b5-9edc-4037-b4b2-6cd1518eb6c6","content":"Since MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 defaults to VSTest when `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` is set, here's what to change to switch to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n### In your `.csproj`:\n\n1. **Remove** (or set to `false`) the VSTest opt-in:\n   ```xml\n   <!-- Delete this line -->\n   <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n   ```\n   MSTest.Sdk ≥ 3.4 defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, so simply removing the property is enough.\n\n2. **No extra PackageReference needed** — the SDK brings in `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` automatically.\n\n### Behavioral changes to be aware of:\n\n| Area | VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|---|\n| CLI runner | `dotnet test` (uses VSTest engine) | `dotnet test` still works, but the test host runs natively |\n| `--filter` syntax | VSTest filter syntax | Same syntax supported |\n| `.runsettings` | Fully supported | Supported, but some adapters differ |\n| TRX logging | Built-in | Add `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` is implicit via SDK; TRX via `--report-trx` |\n\n### Quick checklist:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n-   <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\nAfter the change, run `dotnet test` and verify all tests pass. If you relied on custom VSTest adapters or extensions, check their Microsoft.Testing.Platform compatibility.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c979adcf-ead6-4ae7-b916-2645eca48459","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"0833:44A9F:7E4004F:8C7A46A:69EABEDC"},"id":"9dfdb068-abc1-4ab1-97fe-1222a64c11ba","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:52:54.877Z","parentId":"2c06f5c1-386f-4659-8673-bea1066928be"}
